5 (c) a copy of the written request for information;
6 (d) a copy of the director's response to the written request, if any; and
7 (e) the legislator's proposed reduction to that agency's budget.
8 (5)(6) The committee in possession of the general appropriations act shall schedule a hearing on the
9 complaint within 3 legislative days of receiving the complaint.
10 (a) Notice of the time and place of the hearing must be provided to the legislator and the director of
11 the agency within 48 hours of the hearing.
12 (b) The hearing may be postponed by the presiding officer of the committee if either the legislator
13 or the director of the agency is unavailable to attend in person or cannot attend remotely by electronic means
14 due to hospitalization or catastrophic event. The hearing must be rescheduled by the presiding officer of the
15 committee at the earliest date when both the legislator and the director of the agency are available to attend the
16 hearing.
17 (c) The hearing, discussion of the committee, and vote of the committee must be recorded.
18 (6)(7) After the hearing, the committee may vote to reduce the agency's budget by no more than 5%
19 for failing to provide the requested information.
20 (7)(8) The recording of the hearing, discussion of the committee, and vote of the committee must be
21 provided by the committee clerk to the president of the senate, the speaker of the house, and the governor
22 within 10 days of the committee's vote.
23 (8)(9) The governor shall include the committee's vote in the director's personnel record and may
24 subject the director to disciplinary measures, including termination.
25 (9)(10) For the purposes of this section:
26 (a) "State agency" means a department, board, quasi-judicial board, commission, committee,
